@flexiarg ukrns/separate-evidence-gaps-from-implementation-decisions
@title Separate Evidence Gaps from Implementation Decisions (Sketch)
@verdict early
@keywords sketch, open-questions, hand-off, implementation, evidence-gap, ownership, decision-boundary
@audience UKRN Services design, working-paper authors, board readers, implementers
@tone analytic-foundational
@style sketch
@references [system-coherence/bind-open-questions-to-closure-mechanisms system-coherence/separate-configurable-choices-from-load-bearing-couplings writing-coherence/meta-title]
@summary A decision-supporting paper should separate questions the evidence must settle from choices the implementing organisation must own, so that unresolved evidence needs are not confused with operational discretion.

! conclusion: Some uncertainties belong to the evidence base and must be resolved or explicitly carried forward; others are implementation choices that properly belong to UKRN Services once the design is accepted. A paper that mixes the two makes its own gaps look larger than they are and makes implementation ownership harder to see.

  + context: The current working paper now distinguishes open questions about impact and learning from hand-off questions about resourcing, evaluator configuration, partnerships, and topic priority. That separation is doing real governance work for the reader.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: unresolved evidence need ↔ owned implementation choice.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: separating the two exposes where the paper cannot yet close a claim, and it also exposes where the implementing team cannot defer a judgment by asking for more analysis.

  + THEN:
    Name the evidence gaps explicitly; name the implementation decisions explicitly; and refuse to let one masquerade as the other.

